      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a portable power station?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A larger scale power bank incorporating an MPPT (solar controller), a battery and an inverter, along with various input and output ports. They work in a similar way to a generator, allowing users to power devices and mains appliances where there is no access to grid mains power. Battery sizes (energy capacity) and inverter ratings (output power) vary across different models to offer more cost effective and tailored solutions."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When might a portable power station be used?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "They can be used for almost anything which requires a power supply when there is no access to mains power. Predominantly with campervans and motorhomes. Businesses like off-grid power without the noise and smell of a generator. Festivals often have a no generator policy. Back up during power cuts to keep essential devices and emergency medical equipment running. Many trades and fleets use portable power stations as a cost effective onboard power solution."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are Watt hours and amp hours?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Watt (W) is a rate of power usage. A Watt hour (Wh) is a Watt of power spent every second for an entire hour. A 2000Wh battery would allow you to run an appliance rated at 2000W for one hour or a 1000W appliance for 2 hours. Watt hours can be converted to amp hours by dividing Wattage by voltage (e.g. 1500Wh / 12V = 125Ah)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does peak or surge power mean?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Certain devices, such as items with motors, use more power when they start up than what they use when they are running. A portable power station's surge power will allow a limited amount of extra power to start these devices."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
