      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the difference between Ah and kWh?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Ah (amp hours) measures electrical charge — how much current a battery can supply over one hour. It is commonly used for DC or battery power. Wh (Watt hours) measures energy use or storage and is used for AC or mains power. mAh is more common for small devices like phones, while kWh is used for larger systems such as home batteries and solar storage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the difference between AC and DC power?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In the UK, AC (alternating current) is what comes from your mains sockets — typically 230V AC. It is ideal for powering household appliances. DC (direct current) is the type of power stored in batteries and used by most electronics. Portable power stations convert DC to AC so you can plug in standard UK devices safely."
